@node Internationalization and localization, Substitute, $tring words, Strings and Characters
@subsection Internationalization and localization

A program may need to communicate with its user in the user's
language, and it may have users with different languages.  We do not
want to produce one version of the program for each language, so we
write one internationalized program that can use localization features
to communicate in the user's language.

Apart from the words mentioned here, you will probably want to use
Unicode to write the localized strings; you probably do not need to
use the xchar words (@pxref{Xchars and Unicode}) in that context, but
they are there if you need them.

Moreover, you may need to put placeholders (e.g., for amounts of
currency) in localized strings that you substitute for the real values
later.  The word @word{substitute} and friends (@pxref{Substitute})
have been designed for that purpose.

The basic idea in an internationalized program is that instead of, e.g.,

@source
." Please enter your name:"
@end source

you write

@source
L" Please enter your name:" locale@ type
@end source

In the following examples, we use the locales defined with

@source
locale: de    \ German (generic)
locale: de_AT \ German (as used in Austria)
locale: de_CH \ German (as used in Switzerland)
locale: de_DE \ German (as used in Germany)
@end source

In addition, there are the locales @word{program} and @word{default}.

You can activate a locale, i.e., make it the current locale, with,
e.g.,

@source
lang:de_AT
@end source

Note that, unlike most Forth words, locales are case-sensitive, so
@word{lang:de_at} would not work.

In the following examples, we use the following code to output
localized strings, after first setting the strings (shown later):

@source
L" Please enter your name:" locale@ cr type
L" cauliflower" locale@ cr type
L" street" locale@ cr type
L" something else" locale@ cr type
L" bank [geography]" locale@ cr type
L" bank [finance]" locale@ cr type
@end source

When the current locale is @word{de_AT}, the output is:

@example
Bitte geben Sie Ihren Namen ein:
Karfiol
Strae
something else
Ufer
Bank
@end example

When the current locale is @word{de_CH}, the output is:

@example
Bitte geben Sie Ihren Namen ein:
Blumenkohl
Strasse
something else
Ufer
Bank
@end example

In the localization data used for this example (see below), most of
these localizations are inherited from the locale @word{de}, with the
only @code{de_AT}-specific localization being ``Karfiol'' and the only
@code{de_CH}-specific localization being ``Strasse''.  There is no
@word{de} and no @word{default} localization for ``something else'',
so the text in the string @code{L" something else"} is used (we always
get that if we use the @word{program} locale).

So there is a sequence of fallbacks for looking up localizations: For
the general locale @code{@i{X}_@i{Y}}, the first fallback is to
@code{@i{X}}, next to @word{default}, and finally to @word{program}.
If the current locale's name contains no underscore, the fallback
sequence starts at @word{default}.

The role of the locale @word{default} is twofold: It is a fallback if
there is no more specific localization (typically, if the localization
is missing), as for ``something else''.  In many cases (as for
``something else'') there is no @word{default} localization, and the
fallback continues to the @word{L"} string.  But in some cases (e.g.,
in @code{L" bank [geography]"} and @code{L" bank [finance]"}) these
strings are too developer-oriented, and we put a user-oriented string
(``bank'' for both) in the @word{default} locale.

So how do we provide the localized string for a given @word{program}
string?  A simple way is to use @word{locale!}, e.g.:

@source
lang:de_AT
"Karfiol" L" cauliflower" locale!
@end source

However, defining localizations for all @word{L"} strings with
@word{locale!} is cumbersome and error-prone (you have to use the
exact same spelling for @word{L"} strings with @word{locale!} as
before @word{locale@} in the code).

A better alternative is to use @word{locale-csv-out} after loading the
program to save all its @word{L"} strings and all the existing
localizations to a CSV (comma-separated values) file.  The first
column of this file contains the @word{L"} strings, the others the
various localizations for that string.  E.g., the CSV file for the
example in this section contains:

@example
"program","default","de","de_AT","de_CH","de_DE"
"bank [finance]","bank","Bank","","",""
"bank [geography]","bank","Ufer","","",""
"Please enter your name:","","Bitte geben Sie Ihren Namen ein:","","",""
"cauliflower","","Blumenkohl","Karfiol","",""
"street","","Strae","","Strasse",""
"something else","","","","",""
@end example

The first line contains the names of the locales.  Many entries contain
empty strings; in that case, there is no localization for the
@word{L"} string for the locale of that column (and @word{locale@}
will use the next fallback that is not empty.

The way to add localizations is to edit the CSV file.  This is not
easy with a simple text editor if there are many columns.  One way to
work around this is to use a spreadsheet program or an editor that has
good CSV support.  Another way is to distribute the localizations
across several files (which is also better for letting several people
work on the localizations at the same time).  E.g., one file cpuld
contain the localizations for @word{de} and its variants, while
another could contain the localizations for @word{fr} (French) and its
variants.

Once a localization has been edited into a CSV file, one can load the
CSV file with @word{locale-csv}.  All the locales mentioned in the CSV
file except @word{program} and @word{default} will be defined
automatically; if you use @word{locale-csv}, do not use
@word{locale:}, at least not for the locales in the CSV file.

@word{L"} produces a @dfn{locale-string identifier} (@dfn{lsid}).  An
lsid is an opaque token that occupies a cell, and it identifies the
@word{L"} string independent of the locale (language or
country-specific language variation).

