@node Recognizer order, Defining recognizers, Default recognizers, Recognizers
@subsubsection Recognizer order

You may prefer to use a different recognizer sequence, but with (some
of the) existing recognizers.  You can use the following words for
that:

doc-rec-forth
doc-rec-sequence:
doc-get-recs
doc-set-recs

You probably don't want to create a new recognizer sequence every time
you want to change the system recognizer sequence.  There are several
ways to change an existing recognizer sequence:

@itemize @bullet

@item
Put one or more @word{defer}red words in a recognizer sequence, and
change the recognizer in this word later.  If you do not want such a
deferred word to recognize anything for now, put @word{rec-none} in
it.

@item
Use @word{set-recs} on the recognizer sequence, possibly after getting
the current sequence with @word{get-recs} and modifying it.

@item
The body of a recognizer sequence is a @word{stack}
(@pxref{User-defined Stacks}), and you can use the words for
manipulating stacks on it.  In particular, if you add a recognizer
with @word{>stack}, that recognizer will be tried first; if you add it
with @word{>back}, it will be tried last.

@end itemize

doc-rec-none

Here is an example of adding @word{rec-none} as last recognizer to
the system recognizers:

@source
' rec-none action-of rec-forth get-recs 1+ action-of rec-forth set-recs

\ alternative
' rec-none action-of rec-forth >body >back
@end source

@node Defining recognizers, Defining translation tokens, Recognizer order, Recognizers
@subsubsection Defining recognizers
@cindex recognizer, stack effect
@cindex translation
@cindex translation token

A @dfn{recognizer} is a Forth word with the stack effect @code{(
@i{c-addr u -- translation} )}.  @i{c-addr u} describes the string to
be recognized.  The returned @dfn{translation} is an abstract, but
transparent data type: On the top of stack, there is a single-cell
@dfn{translation token}.  If the recognizer does not recognize the
string, it returns the translation token @word{translate-none}.  If it
does recognize the string, it returns a translation with a different
translation token.  The translation token also identifies how many
other stack items the translation contains and how the translation
will be processed later.

E.g., when you perform

@example
"5" rec-number
@end example

it pushes @code{5 translate-cell} on the stack, which is a translation
with the translation token @word{translate-cell}.

You typically write a recognizer as ordinary colon definition that
examines the string in some way, and then pushes the appropriate
translation.  E.g., a simple variant of @word{rec-tick} can be
implemented as follows:

@source
: rec-tick ( addr u -- translation )
    2dup "`" string-prefix? if
        1 /string find-name dup if
            name>interpret translate-cell exit then
        drop translate-none exit then
    rec-none ;
@end source            

The only appropriate use of a translation is to pass it to one of the
words for performing translation actions (@pxref{Performing
translation actions}).

A number of translation tokens already exist in Gforth and can be used
in a recognizer you write.  If none of them is appropriate for your
recognizer, read the next section about defining your own translation
tokens.

@cindex translation-token words, stack effect
The system-defined translation-token words are documented as removing
some stack items and pushing a complete translation on the stack,
e.g., for @word{translate-cell} @code{( x -- translation )}.  This
makes the documentation uniform and avoids cumbersome descriptions.
However, actually the current translation-token words just push a
cell-sized translation token on the stack (for @word{translate-cell}:
@code{( -- translate-cell )}), and, combined with the additional stack
items (for @word{translate-cell}: @code{( x -- x translate-cell )}),
the result is a translation (for @word{translate-cell}: @code{( x --
translation )}).

@c !! move this further down?
The text interpreter passes the output of the recognizer to a
translation action (@pxref{Performing translation actions}).  Every
translation action removes the translation from the stack, then may
perform additional parsing, and finally performs the interpreting
run-time of the translation token, or the compiling run-time, or the
postponing run-time.

For each system-defined translation token we specify the interpreting
run-time explicitly.  Unless otherwise specified, the compiling
run-time compiles the interpreting run-time.  Unless otherwise
specified, the postponing run-time compiles the compiling run-time.

In the @word{rec-tick} example above, if the recognizer recognizes,
say, @code{`dup}, it returns @i{xt-dup translate-cell}.  If the text
interpreter then performs the compiling action, that action first
removes this translation (these two cells), and compiles code that
pushes @i{xt-dup}.

