@node Base and integer decimal point, String to number conversion, Number conversion, Number conversion
@subsection Base and integer decimal point
@cindex number conversion, @code{base}
@cindex integer conversion, @code{base}

By default, the number base used for integer number conversion is
given by the contents of the variable @code{base}.  @word{Base}
affects both input integer conversion (unless a number prefix is used,
@pxref{Literals in source code}) and output integer conversion (unless
a base-specific word such as @word{h.} or @word{dec.} is used,
@pxref{Simple numeric output}, @pxref{Integer to string conversion}).  In
Gforth, non-decimal @word{base} disables floating-point conversion.

Note that a lot of confusion can result from unexpected values of
@code{base}.  If you change @code{base} anywhere, make sure to save
the old value and restore it afterwards; better yet, use
@code{base-execute}, which does this for you.

In general I recommend keeping @code{base} decimal; For dealing with
the popular non-decimal bases, use number prefixes for inputting them
(@pxref{Literals in source code}) and @word{h.} and
@word{base-execute} for outputting them.

doc-base-execute
doc-base
doc-hex
doc-decimal
doc-dpl

@cindex number conversion - traps for the unwary
@noindent
Number conversion has a number of traps for the unwary:

@itemize @bullet
@item
A . in or at the end of a number by default indicates a double number, not a
floating-point number.
@item
Input FP conversion does not happen if @word{base} is non-decimal.
@item
You cannot determine the current number base using the code sequence
@code{base @@ .} -- the number base is always 10 in the current number
base. Instead, use something like @code{base @@ dec.}
@item
There is a word @code{bin} but it does @i{not} set the number base!
(@pxref{General files}).
@item
Standard Forth requires the @code{.} of a double-precision number to be the
final character in the string.  Gforth allows the @code{.} to be
anywhere.
@item
The input integer conversion process does not check for overflow.
Instead, you get a value in the range of the result integer type
(single or double cell) that is congruent with the input number modulo
the number of values in the integer type (e.g., modulo 2^128 for
doubles with 64-bit cells).
@end itemize

Words affected by @word{base} are @word{rec-number} (@pxref{Default
recognizers}), @word{>number} (@pxref{String to number conversion}),
and the words described in the sections @ref{Simple numeric output},
and @ref{Integer to string conversion}. @word{Rec-number} sets
@word{dpl}.




